    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper tries to make black hole physics more directly testable by rewriting standard formulas \u2014 for how light bends near a black hole and how it thermally radiates \u2014 in terms of the shadow size seen by telescopes like the EHT, rather than the black hole's mass, which can only be inferred indirectly. The review board found the central mathematical idea sound for the simplest (Kerr) case, but found the headline claims for modified-gravity black holes either unverifiable (key constants are never defined) or internally inconsistent (quoted percentages differ between sections). The most important caveat is that several numerical predictions cannot be independently checked from the paper as written.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper re-parameterizes the weak deflection angle and semiclassical Hawking thermodynamics for Kerr, Kerr-MOG, and rotating Horndeski spacetimes by substituting a locally unique M(R_sh) inversion \u2014 justified via the Implicit Function Theorem \u2014 in place of the unobservable bare mass. The basic Kerr algebra (Eqs. 26, 28, 30) was confirmed dimensionally and algebraically consistent by two of three reviewers after cross-checking the LaTeX source. However, the IFT argument is only explicitly verified for the Schwarzschild and slow-rotation Kerr limits and is not independently checked for the MOG and Horndeski metrics. The Horndeski sector introduces dimensionless constants (\u03ba, \u03b7_E or equivalent structural functions) that are never derived from the stated metric components, making the headline luminosity-deviation claim (variously quoted as ~20%, ~36%, and ~52% in different parts of the manuscript) unverifiable. Additional systematic concerns include: the slow-rotation equatorial approximation applied to likely high-spin M87*; reduction of the asymmetric rotating shadow to a single scalar R_sh without justification; and uncontrolled greybody/superradiant corrections to the Stefan-Boltzmann luminosity baseline. The \"thermodynamic-optical duality\" framing and \"degeneracy breaking\" claim overstate what is a local, parameter-fixed change of variables."
    }
